### YANG Data Model for ACaaS with UDP Tunnel Support
*   **Presenter:** John Kaippallimalil
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-dmm-udp-tunnel-acaas-extn](https://datatracker.ietf.org/draft-ietf-dmm-udp-tunnel-acaas-extn/)
*   **Slides:** [A YANG Data Model for Attachment Circuit as a Service with UDP Tunnel Support](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-dmm-a-yang-data-model-for-attachment-circuit-as-a-service-with-udp-tunnel-support-00)
*   **Discussion:**
    *   The draft is a Standards Track document separated from the informational slicing draft. It defines a Layer 3 bearer with UDP tunnel support, allowing configuration of port ranges and boundaries.
    *   The YANG structure has been compiled with zero errors and reviewed by the operations management area.
    *   The latest revision (v01) addresses early review comments to comply with RFC 9907 registration templates (adjusting registry group and sub-registry naming). 
    *   The draft is considered mature and ready for Working Group Last Call.

### MUP Architecture v02 Update
*   **Presenter:** Satoru Matsushima
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-dmm-mup-architecture](https://datatracker.ietf.org/draft-ietf-dmm-mup-architecture/)
*   **Slides:** [MUP Architecture v02 update](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-dmm-mup-architecture-v02-update-00)
*   **Discussion:**
    *   Revision 02 introduces distributed home-routed roaming with multiple home operators (Section 7.5).
    *   Key protocol updates include:
        *   **ST2 Route Update:** Steers packets to destination interwork segments (e.g., N3/N9) and enables endpoint translation (FTID translation).
        *   **MUP Extended Community:** Added an "interwork segment" type to isolate routing/addressing policies for multiple home operators (e.g., separating overlapping N9 address spaces).
        *   **Security Considerations (Section 9):** Fully rewritten.
    *   Tom Hill noted that the forthcoming SRv6 security considerations draft is nearing completion and must be referenced in this draft. He also cautioned about using the term "inter-domain" due to potential standard ambiguities. Satoru Matsushima clarified that the roaming use case represents legacy interconnection rather than inter-domain SRv6, but agreed that the terminology needs careful, verbose refinement.

### Mobile Traffic Steering (MTS)
*   **Presenter:** Marco Liebsch (online)
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-dmm-mts](https://datatracker.ietf.org/draft-ietf-dmm-mts/)
*   **Slides:** [Mobile Traffic Steering](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-dmm-mobile-traffic-steering-00)
*   **Discussion:**
    *   Revision 02 incorporates review comments from John Kaippallimalil and Carlos J. Bernardos, adding text to the security considerations section and moving the extensible information model (traffic, path, UPA, and DPN chain attributes) to the appendix.
    *   Marco Liebsch requested feedback on the non-terrestrial network (NTN) node abnormality use case diagram, potential additions to relocation scenarios, and how the draft applies to future 3GPP 6G architectures (referencing TR 23.801).
    *   On integrating Time-Variant Routing (TVR) work, Marco Liebsch suggested mapping out-of-band TVR retrieval via the DPN supplementary information URI rather than recreating TVR attributes within the MTS model.

### SRv6 Mobile User Plane Architecture Discussion
*   **Presenter:** Teppei Kamata
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-dmm-srv6mob-arch](https://datatracker.ietf.org/draft-ietf-dmm-srv6mob-arch/)
*   **Slides:** [architecture-discussion-on-srv6-mobile-user-plane-03](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-dmm-architecture-discussion-on-srv6-mobile-user-plane-03-00)
*   **Discussion:**
    *   This informational draft outlines why SRv6 is a strong fit for MUP by transforming session-based topologies (GTP-U) into a destination-based routing paradigm, improving scalability from $O(N^2)$ to $O(N)$ for any-to-any communications.
    *   Revision 03 highlights the benefits of the SRv6 micro-segment (uSID / Next-C-SID, RFC 9800) flavor, which minimizes MTU overhead and improves latency/jitter for URLLC, slicing, and edge computing.
    *   John Kaippallimalil suggested adding further architectural details on the session controller's role to make the scaling benefits clearer for casual readers.
    *   Tingji Ge queried whether the architecture natively simplifies any-to-any communication scalability. Teppei Kamata confirmed that replacing endpoint-pair tunnel sessions with native IP destination reachability is the primary mechanism.

### Mobile User Plane Evolution: 5G & 6G
*   **Presenter:** Tingji Ge
*   **Slides:** [Mobile User Plane Evolution: 5G & 6G](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-dmm-mobile-user-plane-evolution-5g-6g-00)
*   **Discussion:**
    *   Tingji Ge presented on 3GPP's ongoing 6G user plane study (TR 23.801), highlighting tasks like CP-UP disaggregation (CP buffering and CP-constructed end markers) and UP flexibility through the Serving UPF (SUPF) and Anchor UPF (AUPF) split.
    *   The study emphasizes transport-agnostic requirements but includes ongoing debates regarding native SRv6 replacing GTP-U versus overlay tunnels (GTP-U over SRv6/MPLS).
    *   Satoru Matsushima questioned whether SRv6 over MPLS is consistent with transport-agnostic goals.
    *   Erik Kline noted that since IETF participants understand network routing protocols better than 3GPP, IETF should propose robust solutions (such as partial GTP-U replacement and compute integration) to 3GPP.

### Requirements of SRv6 for 6G User Plane
*   **Presenter:** Xiaohu Xu
*   **Slides:** [Requirements of SRv6 for 6G User Plane](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-dmm-requirements-of-srv6-for-6g-user-plane-00)
*   **Discussion:**
    *   The presentation outlined current GTP-U constraints in 6G (fixed routing paths, reconfiguration latency, single-dimensional QoS) and detailed how SRv6 path, service, and application programmability address these limits.
    *   Successful deployment will require tight coordination between the core network control plane (SMF/AMF) and the transport network controller for path computation, SLA-to-SID mapping, and continuous state synchronization.
    *   John Kaippallimalil inquired whether the co-authors have analyzed multi-domain routing aspects in roaming networks. Xiaohu Xu agreed to add analysis of roaming scenarios.
    *   Satoru Matsushima and Erik Kline suggested that Xiaohu Xu and Tingji Ge collaborate to unify 6G requirements and potentially draft a liaison to 3GPP informing them of IETF data plane activities.

